    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac). Native groves near the town of Walnut Creek in Contra Costa Co. are
the best known. Naturalized stands also occur along Walnut Creek near Lafayette.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Native groves on the banks of the Sacramento River occur near Walnut Grove in Sacramento Co., but those in Solano Co. are extirpated. Recent sampling of naturalized occurrences in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007) and along the main Sacramento River (Vaghti 2003) include individual walnut trees in stands of other riparian alliances; they found walnut stands in ecological settings intermediate between the <i>Populus fremontii</i> and the <i>Quercus lobata</i> alliances. During sampling along Cottonwood Creek, a tributary of the Sacramento River, Harris (1987) also found walnut trees in cottonwood and valley oak forests.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Am). Groves that are probably non-native occur in Wooden Valley east of Napa.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bf). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Walnut growers use <i>J. hindsii </i>and backcrosses with either English walnut (<i>J. regia</i>)â€”the Paradox hybrid created by Luther Burbankâ€”or three other North American black walnuts (<i>J. nigra, J. major, </i>and 130 <i>J. californica</i>) as rootstock for English walnut orchards in the state. These hybrids are resistant to several important soil-borne pests. Kirk (2003) considered the naturalized populations to be hybrids largely with <i>J. major</i>. People also plant <i>J. nigra </i>near houses and along roadsides. Many orchards are adjacent to riparian vegetation, and animals (ground squirrels, jays, etc.) and water disperse the walnuts widely in both rural and suburban settings (Vaghti and Greco 2007). 

While previously only one native stand of <i>Juglans hindsii </i>appeared to be recognized as viable (CNPS 2007), many native and mixed hybrid stands are now recognized. Hybridization between the native populations and cultivated walnuts still endangers the species. For example, walnut hybrids at Bidwell-Sacramento River State Park appear invasive and are taking over the parkâ€™s riparian forests. We should add these walnuts to the list of invasive taxa when considering restoration of riparian forests in northern California (Vaghti and Greco 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

